C#

para rodar o código que escreveu, sempre use "mono", exemplo: "mono App.exe", como mostrado no link a seguir: https://www.mono-project.com/docs/getting-started/mono-basics/ 


Pelo menos rodando no terminal pois essa é a forma de rodar C# no Linux. 



RUN THE CODE ON VSCODE TERMINAL: 

The .NET Build System does not work with loose .cs files (or f# or vb for that matter), it needs at least a Project. You can generate a Project file by using dotnet new <template> as follows:


• md MyProject
• cd MyProject
• dotnet new console 


Now you have a folder MyProject, containing MyProject.csproj and a default Program.cs file.
To run it, you can now do: 

• dotnet run 


This will open and read the .csproj file, it will build all the sourcefiles and packages that are referenced inside it into an executable, and then it will run that. 



Fonte da bela descoberta acima: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/56775156/cant-run-code-using-dotnet-run-command-in-visual-studio-couldnt-find-a-proje/56775234 

Obs: no arquivo "launch.json", na parte: "project", o nome no final do arquivo fica na extensão ".dll"  



